reviewText: Set in 1820s Texas, COMANCHE TERRITORY features frontiersman Jim Bowie.After he's attacked by a band of Indians, Bowie (Carey) is rescued by ex-Congressman Dan'l Seeger (Geer), who's wounded in the shoulder during the fight. Bowie removes the bullet; both he and Seeger are captured by the Comanches. The straight-talking Bowie impresses an old Chief (Cordoba) by explaining how to make his famous knife. The Comanches agree to a treaty renewal that would permit silver mining on tribal land. Bowie and Seeger must then go up against bank and saloon owner Katie Howard (O'Hara), who Dan'l believes wounded him and stole the treaty papers.As of 1/09, "Comanche Territory" was not available on DVD.Also recommended:THE BURNING HILLS(1956) stars Tab Hunter and Natalie Wood in a romantic western adapted from Louis L'Amour's novel.  (VHS only)Parenthetical number preceding title is a 1 to 10 viewer poll rating found at a film resource website.(5.1) Comanche Territory (1950) - Maureen O'Hara/Macdonald Carey/Will Geer/Charles Drake/Pedro de Cordoba/Ian MacDonald/Glenn Strange  (Uncredited: Iron Eyes Cody/I. Stanford Jolley)

reviewText: Maureen O'Hara in one of her best roles, in the clever portrayal of a beautiful woman who can wear the pants in her business, drink her counterpart under the table, tough it out when the Indians strike, and match wits with the best of them as she cleans them out playing poker!  In the end, her feminine side triumphs as she conquers Mac Donald Carey's heart, hook line and sinker...

reviewText: I love westerns, but this movie stinks.  Maureen O'Hara ruins every movie she is in except the original "Parent Trap" which is a terrific movie.  A lot of this movie is shot using  the green screen technique.  And the historical basis of this movie is ridiculous.  A western with settlers stealing land in the far west during the presidency of Andrew Jackson.  Huh?  Just awful.
